\n| Favorite Family Movie\n|\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"|'''[[Teen Choice Awards]]'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://theenvelope.latimes.com/env-2008-teen-choice-awards-scorecard17jun17,0,2603341.htmlstory |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |publisher=[[Arthur Ochs Sulzberger, Jr.]] |date=June 17, 2008 |accessdate=August 6, 2013 |title=2008 Teen Choice Awards winners and nominees |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20080912051322/http://theenvelope.latimes.com/env-2008-teen-choice-awards-scorecard17jun17,0,2603341.htmlstory |archivedate=September 12, 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n| Choice Summer Movie: Comedy\n|\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|'''[[Visual Effects Society Awards 2008|Visual Effects Society]]'''<ref>{{cite news|title='Iron Man' leads pack at VES noms|url=https://variety.com/2009/film/awards/iron-man-leads-pack-at-ves-noms-1117998754/|accessdate=October 21, 2015|work=Variety|date=January 19, 2009}}</ref>\n| Outstanding Animated Character in an Animated Motion Picture\n| [[Jack Black]]<br />Dan Wagner<br />Nico Marlet<br />Peter Farson\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Outstanding Animation in an Animated Motion Picture\n| Markus Manninen<br />Dan Wagner<br />Alex Parkinson<br />Raymond Zibach\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Outstanding Effects Animation in an Animated Motion Picture\n| Markus Manninen<br />Alex Parkinson<br />Amaury Aubel<br />Li-Ming 'Lawrence' Lee\n| {{Nom}}\n|}\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Kung Fu Panda\n| type       = [[Soundtrack]]\n| artist     = [[Hans Zimmer]] and [[John Powell (composer)|John Powell]]\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = June 3, 2008\n| recorded   = 2008\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Soundtrack]]\n| length     = 60:16\n| label      = [[Interscope Records|Interscope]]\n| producer   = [[Hans Zimmer]]<br/>[[John Powell (composer)|John Powell]]<br/>[[The Underdogs (production team)|The Underdogs]] <small>(track 17)</small>\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\nAs with most DreamWorks animated movies, composer [[Hans Zimmer]] scored ''Kung Fu Panda''. Zimmer visited China to absorb the culture and got to know the [[China National Symphony Orchestra|Chinese National Symphony]] as part of his preparation; in addition, [[Timbaland]] also contributed to the soundtrack.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalledger.com/cgi-bin/artman/exec/view.cgi?archive=17&num=16128&printer=1 |title=The Big Screen Scene |first=Stephanie |last=DuBois |author2=Emily Feimster |work=National Ledger |date=September 18, 2007 |accessdate=June 7, 2008}}</ref> The soundtrack also includes a partially rewritten version of the classic song, \"[[Kung Fu Fighting]]\", performed by [[Cee-Lo Green]] and Jack Black for the end credits. Furthermore, in some versions, the ending credit was sung by [[Rain (entertainer)|Rain]]. Although Zimmer was originally announced as the main composer of the film, during a test screening, CEO of DreamWorks Animation SKG [[Jeffrey Katzenberg]] announced that composer [[John Powell (composer)|John Powell]] would also be contributing to the score. This marked the first collaboration in eight years for the two, who had previously worked together on DreamWorks' ''[[The Road to El Dorado]]'' and the action thriller ''[[Chill Factor (1999 film)|Chill Factor]]''. A soundtrack album was released by [[Interscope Records]] on June 3, 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/film/news/e3i595b48df06c95e2eed05e9c3eb45a08c\n|title=Jack Black, Cee-Lo cover ''Kung Fu Fighting'' |first=Jonathan |last=Cohen |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=May 12, 2008 |accessdate=June 4, 2008 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080517054016/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/film/news/e3i595b48df06c95e2eed05e9c3eb45a08c |archivedate = May 17, 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Sequels==\nA sequel, ''[[Kung Fu Panda 2]]'', was released on Thursday, May 26, 2011,<ref name=\"sequel\">{{cite web|title=Kung Fu Panda 2 Officially Headed to Theaters in 2011 |url=http://www.firstshowing.net/2008/10/01/kung-fu-panda-2-officially-headed-to-theaters-in-2011/ |work=FirstShowing.net |date=October 1, 2008 |accessdate=June 12, 2009}}</ref> to good reviews (Rotten Tomatoes rating of 81%). It was released in 3-D and was directed by [[Jennifer Yuh Nelson]] (who directed the 2-D opening sequence of the first film) with the original cast returning. The story features a new villain with a mysterious weapon so powerful it threatens the existence of kung fu, and Po must additionally confront his past.\n\nA second sequel, ''[[Kung Fu Panda 3]]'' was announced as a co-production between DreamWorks Animation and Shanghai-based [[Oriental DreamWorks]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Rising Dreams in the Orient: Oriental DreamWorks To Establish Headquarters in Xuhui|url=http://ir.dreamworksanimation.com/releasedetail.cfm?ReleaseID=698481|archive-url=https://archive.today/20121208192232/http://ir.dreamworksanimation.com/releasedetail.cfm?ReleaseID=698481|url-status=dead|archive-date=December 8, 2012|accessdate=August 7, 2012|newspaper=DreamWorks Animation|date=August 6, 2012}}</ref> ''Kung Fu Panda 3'' was released on January 29, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/kung-fu-panda-3-release-788851|title='Kung Fu Panda 3' Release Date Moves Up Two Months|author=Rebecca Ford|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=([[Prometheus Global Media]])|date=April 14, 2015|accessdate=April 15, 2015}}</ref> DreamWorks Animation CEO [[Jeffrey Katzenberg]] has said that the series could see 3 more sequels after ''Kung Fu Panda 3'', bringing it to a six-film series.<ref name=Future>{{cite news|last=O'Hara|first=Helen|title=Katzenberg Talks DreamWorks Sequels|url=https://www.empireonline.com/news/story.asp?NID=29638|accessdate=September 7, 2011|newspaper=Empire|date=December 3, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Spin-offs==\n===Manga===\nA [[manga]] based on the film was released in Japan in ''[[Kerokero Ace]]'' magazine's September 2008 issue.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2008-07-29/america-kung-fu-panda-film-gets-manga-in-japan |title=America's Kung Fu Panda Film Gets Manga in Japan (Updated) |work=Anime News Network |date=May 12, 2009 |accessdate=May 16, 2009}}</ref> It is written by Hanten Okuma and illustrated by Takafumi Adachi.<ref name=\"animecentral\">{{cite web|url=http://www.animecentral.com/news/story.aspx?ID=447|title=Kung Fu Panda Manga Released in Japan|publisher=Anime Central|accessdate=May 20, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101013221547/http://animecentral.com/news/story.aspx?ID=447|archivedate=October 13, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Television series===\nA television series titled ''[[Kung Fu Panda: Legends of Awesomeness]]'' aired on [[Nickelodeon (TV channel)|Nickelodeon]] with its premiere on September 19, 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nick.com/shows/kung-fu-panda-legends-of-awesomeness/|title=Kung Fu Panda: Legends of Awesomeness {{!}} Nickelodeon |accessdate=September 18, 2011}}</ref> From the cast of ''Kung Fu Panda'', only Lucy Liu and James Hong reprised their roles, of Master Viper and Mr. Ping respectively.<ref>{{cite press release|author1=Nickelodeon|title=Megahit Martial Arts Panda is Back as Nickelodeon and Dreamworks Animation Premiere Kung Fu Panda: Legends of Awesomeness, New CG-Animated Series, Monday, Nov. 7, at 5:30 P.M. (ET/PT)|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/megahit-martial-arts-panda-is-back-as-nickelodeon-and-dreamworks-animation-premiere-kung-fu-panda--legends-of-awesomeness-new-cg-animated-series-monday-nov-7-at-530-pm-etpt-132549638.html|accessdate=October 26, 2011|agency=PR Newswire|date=October 25, 2011}}</ref> In the series, Po continues to defend the Valley of Peace from all kinds of villains, while making mistakes, learning about the history of kung fu, and meeting other kung fu masters. In the United States, the series ended its run on June 29, 2016, with a total of three seasons and 80 episodes. However, prior to premiering in the U.S., the final few episodes first premiered in Germany from December 30, 2014 to January 7, 2015.\n\n''[[Kung Fu Panda: The Paws of Destiny]]'' is an animated web television series produced by DreamWorks Animation released for Amazon Prime on November 16, 2018. It is the second TV series in the Kung Fu Panda franchise following Kung Fu Panda: Legends of Awesomeness. Developer Mitch Watson has confirmed that Mick Wingert will reprise his role from Legends of Awesomeness as Po.[3]\n\n===Holiday special===\nThe ''[[Kung Fu Panda Holiday Special]]'' was aired on [[NBC]] Wednesday, November 24, 2010.<ref>[http://www.thefutoncritic.com/news/2010/09/07/nbc-and-dreamworks-animation-bring-one-of-a-kind-animated-programming-to-audiences-at-home-for-the-holidays-with-new-original-specials-scared-shrekless-and-kung-fu-panda-holiday-special/20100907nbc01/ NBC and DreamWorks Animation Bring One of a Kind Animated Programming to Audiences at Home For the Holidays with New Original Specials ''Scared Shrekless'' and ''Kung Fu Panda Holiday Special''], NBC via The Futon Critic, September 9, 2010 Retrieved 26 September 26, 2010</ref>\n\n==Video game==\n{{Main|Kung Fu Panda (video game)}}\nA video game adaptation of the film was published by [[Activision]] on June 3, 2008.<ref>{{cite news|title=Kung Fu Panda Video Game Demo Now Available on Xbox Live Marketplace|url=http://xbox360.gamespy.com/xbox-360/luxoflux-next-gen-project/870948p1.html|accessdate=March 27, 2012|newspaper=GameSpy|date=May 1, 2008}}</ref> The game was released for [[PlayStation 3]], [[Xbox 360]], [[Wii]], [[PlayStation 2]], [[Nintendo DS]] and [[computer platform|PC]] platforms. The plot follows the same basic plot as the film, but with Tai Lung portrayed as the leader of various gangs that surround the Valley of Peace, which Po, who possesses some basic martial art skills which can be upgraded as the game progresses, must defeat. The game was released on [[Microsoft Windows]], as well as multiple consoles. However the Windows version has been discontinued. The game received mostly positive reviews; it scored a [[Metacritic]] rating of 76% from critics<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=September 1, 2008 |url=http://www.metacritic.com/games/platforms/xbox360/kungfupanda |title=Kung Fu Panda |work=Metacritic}}</ref> and a 7.5 out of 10 from [[IGN]].<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=September 1, 2008 |url=http://xbox360.ign.com/articles/880/880257p1.html |title=Kung Fu Panda Review |work=IGN |date=June 9, 2008 |last=Brudvig |first=Erik}}</ref> In 2009, it won the International Animated Film Society's Annie Award for Best Animated Video Game, \"in recognition of creative excellence in the art of animation.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.annieawards.org/ |title=Kung Fu Panda dominates the Annie Awards |work=The Annie Awards |date=January 30, 2009 |accessdate=February 5, 2009}}</ref>\n\n== Literature ==\n* 2008: [[Susan Korman]]: ''Kung Fu Panda - The Junior [[Novel]]'' ([[Novelization]]), HarperFestival, {{ISBN|978-0-0614-3463-1}}\n\n== Lawsuits ==\nDreamWorks Animation was sued in 2011 by a writer, Terence Dunn, for allegedly stealing the idea for ''Kung Fu Panda'' from him.<ref name=THRJurySides>{{cite news|last=Belloni|first=Matthew|title=Jury Sides With DreamWorks Animation in 'Kung Fu Panda' Case (Exclusive)|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/thr-esq/jury-sides-dreamworks-animation-kung-215019|accessdate=December 25, 2013|newspaper=The Hollywood Reporter|date=July 25, 2011}}</ref> Dunn alleged that DreamWorks Animation had stolen his pitch for a \"spiritual kung-fu fighting panda bear\" which he sent to a DreamWorks executive in 2001.<ref name=THRJurySides /> DreamWorks Animation denied any wrongdoing and after a two-week trial the jurors found in favor of DreamWorks.<ref name=THRJurySides />\n\nIn 2011, another lawsuit was brought against the studio by an illustrator named Jayme Gordon. Gordon had supposedly created characters under the name \"Kung Fu Panda Power\" and registered them with the [[U.S. Copyright Office]] in 2000.<ref name=AnotherLawsuit>{{cite news|last=Gardner|first=Eriq|title=DreamWorks Hit With Another Lawsuit Over 'Kung Fu Panda' (Exclusive)|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/blogs/thr-esq/dreamworks-hit-lawsuit-kung-fu-101075|accessdate=June 25, 2014|newspaper=The Hollywood Reporter|date=February 17, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110220041709/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/blogs/thr-esq/dreamworks-hit-lawsuit-kung-fu-101075|archivedate=February 20, 2011}}</ref> He had allegedly pitched this concept work to Disney while Jeffrey Katzenberg, who later left Disney and formed DreamWorks Animation in 1994, was working there. Gordon withdrew his claim just before the trial was due to take place.<ref name=WithdrawnClaim>{{cite news|last=Gardner|first=Eriq|title=DreamWorks Animation Wins Big 'Kung Fu Panda' Lawsuit (Exclusive)|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/thr-esq/dreamworks-animation-wins-big-kung-597254|accessdate=June 25, 2014|newspaper=The Hollywood Reporter|date=July 31, 2013}}</ref> On December 20, 2015, federal prosecutors charged Gordon with four counts of [[wire fraud]] and three counts of [[perjury]] for allegedly fabricating and backdating drawings to support the claims in his lawsuit, and for allegedly tracing some of his drawings from a [[The Walt Disney Company|Disney]] ''[[The Lion King|Lion King]]'' coloring book.<ref name=BGFraudCharges>{{cite news|last=Valencia|first=Milton|title=Randolph Man Accused of Fraud in 'Kung Fu Panda' Suit Case |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2015/12/21/man-charged-with-fraud-kung-panda-suit-case/gfldvAUUhgD9KGIaJkqi9H/story.html|accessdate=December 21, 2015|newspaper=The Boston Globe|date=December 21, 2011}}</ref> On November 18, 2016, Gordon was convicted for wire fraud and perjury, facing a sentence of up to 25 years in prison.<ref name=\"CBConvictedOfFraud\">{{cite web|last1=Amidi|first1=Amid|title=Fake 'Kung Fu Panda' Creator Convicted of Fraud, Faces Up To 25 Years in Prison|url=http://www.cartoonbrew.com/law/fake-kung-fu-panda-creator-convicted-fraud-faces-25-years-prison-145156.html|publisher=Cartoon Brew|accessdate=November 20, 2016|date=November 19, 2016}}</ref> In May 2017, he was sentenced to two years in federal prison and ordered to pay $3 million in restitution.<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Robb |first1=David |title=\u2018Kung Fu Panda\u2019 Hoaxer Gets 2-Year Prison Term In $12M Fraud Scheme |url=https://deadline.com/2017/05/kung-fu-panda-fraud-sentence-two-years-prison-1202083366/ |magazine=Deadline |accessdate=March 30, 2019 |date=May 3, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Legend of Kung Fu Rabbit]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Kung Fu Panda}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.dreamworks.com/movies/kung-fu-panda}}\n* {{IMDb title|0441773|Kung Fu Panda}}\n* {{bcdb title|65706|Kung Fu Panda}}\n* {{Amg movie|354676|Kung Fu Panda}}\n* {{Rotten-tomatoes|kung_fu_panda|Kung Fu Panda}}\n* {{Metacritic film|kung-fu-panda|Kung Fu Panda}}\n* {{Mojo title|kungfupanda|Kung Fu Panda}}\n\n{{Kung Fu Panda}}\n{{DreamWorks animated films}}\n{{John Stevenson}}\n{{Mark Osborne}}\n{{Annie Award for Best Animated Feature}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Cartoon|Animation|Film|United States}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Kung Fu Panda films]]\n[[Category:2008 films]]\n[[Category:2008 animated films]]\n[[Category:2008 computer-animated films]]\n[[Category:2000s action comedy films]]\n[[Category:2000s adventure comedy films]]\n[[Category:2000s American animated films]]\n[[Category:2000s children's comedy films]]\n[[Category:2000s fantasy-comedy films]]\n[[Category:2008 martial arts films]]\n[[Category:American action comedy films]]\n[[Category:American adventure comedy films]]\n[[Category:American children's animated comedy films]]\n[[Category:American children's animated fantasy films]]\n[[Category:American computer-animated films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:Animated action films]]\n[[Category:Animated adventure films]]\n[[Category:Animated comedy films]]\n[[Category:Animated films about animals]]\n[[Category:Animated films about revenge]]\n[[Category:Anime-influenced Western animation]]\n[[Category:Annie Award winners]]\n[[Category:Anthropomorphic martial artists]]\n[[Category:Best Animated Feature Annie Award winners]]\n[[Category:Films directed by John Stevenson]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Mark Osborne]]\n[[Category:DreamWorks Animation animated films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:IMAX films]]\n[[Category:American martial arts films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Hans Zimmer]]\n[[Category:Films scored by John Powell]]\n[[Category:Films about giant pandas]]\n[[Category:Films adapted into television programs]]\n[[Category:Films featuring anthropomorphic characters]]\n[[Category:Films using computer-generated imagery]]\n[[Category:Kung fu films]]\n[[Category:Martial arts films]]\n[[Category:Martial arts comedy films]]\n[[Category:Paramount Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Paramount Pictures animated films]]\n[[Category:Wuxia films]]\n[[Category:Films set in Imperial China]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Jonathan Aibel and Glenn Berger]]\n[[Category:2008 directorial debut films]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the film|the franchise|Kung Fu Panda (franchise)|other uses|Kung Fu Panda (disambiguation)}}\n{{short description|2008 film directed by John Stevenson and Mark Osborne}}\n{{Use American English|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Kung Fu Panda\n| image          = kungfupanda.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[John Stevenson (director)|John Stevenson]]<br />[[Mark Osborne (filmmaker)|Mark Osborne]]\n| producer       = Melissa Cobb\n| screenplay     = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Jonathan Aibel and Glenn Berger|Jonathan Aibel]]\n* [[Jonathan Aibel and Glenn Berger|Glenn Berger]]}}\n| story          = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Ethan Reiff and Cyrus Voris|Ethan Reiff]]\n* [[Ethan Reiff and Cyrus Voris|Cyrus Voris]]}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Jack Black]]\n* [[Dustin Hoffman]]\n* [[Angelina Jolie]]\n* [[Ian McShane]]\n* [[Seth Rogen]]\n* [[Lucy Liu]]\n* [[David Cross]]\n* [[Randall Duk Kim]]\n* [[James Hong]]\n* [[Dan Fogler]]\n* [[Michael Clarke Duncan]]\n* [[Jackie Chan]]}}<!-- PER CREDITS BILLING. -->\n| music          = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Hans Zimmer]]\n* [[John Powell (composer)|John Powell]]}}\n| cinematography = [[Yong Duk Jhun]]\n| editing        = Clare Knight\n| studio         = [[DreamWorks Animation]]\n| distributor    = [[Paramount Pictures]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2008|5|15|[[2008 Cannes Film Festival|Cannes Film Festival]]|2008|06|06|United States|2008|6|26|Australia|2008|7|4|United Kingdom||2008|08|01|Finland|2008|08|29|Italy|2008|9|5|Cyprus}}\n| runtime        = 95 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $130 million\n| gross          = $631.7 million\n}}\n'''''Kung Fu Panda''''' is a 2008 American [[Computer animation|computer-animated]] ''[[wuxia]]'' [[comedy film]] produced by [[DreamWorks Animation]] and distributed by [[Paramount Pictures]].{{efn|In July 2014, the film's distribution rights were purchased by [[DreamWorks Animation]] from [[Paramount Pictures]] and transferred to [[20th Century Fox]]<ref>{{cite news|last1=Chney|first1=Alexandra|title=DreamWorks Animation Q2 Earnings Fall Short of Estimates, SEC Investigation Revealed|url=https://variety.com/2014/biz/news/dreamworks-animation-q2-earnings-fall-short-of-estimates-1201271262/|accessdate=July 30, 2014|work=Variety|date=July 29, 2014}}</ref> before reverting to [[Universal Pictures|Universal Studios]] in 2018.}} It was directed by [[John Stevenson (director)|John Stevenson]] (in his directorial debut) and [[Mark Osborne (filmmaker)|Mark Osborne]], and stars the voices of [[Jack Black]], [[Dustin Hoffman]], [[Angelina Jolie]], [[Ian McShane]], [[Seth Rogen]], [[Lucy Liu]], [[David Cross]], [[Randall Duk Kim]], [[James Hong]], [[Dan Fogler]], [[Michael Clarke Duncan]], and [[Jackie Chan]]. The film is set in a version of ancient China populated by anthropomorphic [[Talking animals in fiction|talking animals]] and revolves around a bumbling panda named [[Po (Kung Fu Panda)|Po]], a [[kung fu]] enthusiast. When an evil kung fu warrior named Tai Lung is foretold to escape from prison, Po is unwittingly named the \"Dragon Warrior\", that was destined to defeat him.<ref>{{cite news|accessdate=September 1, 2008|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7560194.stm|title=Kung Fu Panda sequel in pipeline|work=BBC|date=August 14, 2008}}</ref>\n\nThe film was originally conceived by Michael Lachance, a DreamWorks Animation executive. It was originally intended to be a parody of martial arts films, but director Stevenson decided instead to make an action comedy [[wuxia]] film that incorporates the [[hero's journey]] [[narrative]] [[archetype]] for the lead character. The computer animation in the film was more complex than anything DreamWorks had done before. As with most DreamWorks Animation films, [[Hans Zimmer]] (this time collaborating with [[John Powell (composer)|John Powell]]) scored ''Kung Fu Panda''. He visited China to absorb the culture and get to know the [[China National Symphony Orchestra]] as part of his preparation.\n \t\n''Kung Fu Panda'' premiered in the United States on June 6, 2008. The film received positive reviews upon release. ''Kung Fu Panda'' opened in 4,114 theaters, grossing $20.3&nbsp;million on its opening day and $60.2&nbsp;million on its opening weekend, resulting in the number one position at the box office. The film became DreamWorks' biggest opening for a non-sequel film, the highest grossing animated film of the year worldwide, and also had the fourth-largest opening weekend for a DreamWorks film at the American and Canadian box office, behind all three ''[[Shrek]]'' sequels.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://today.msnbc.msn.com/id/37302907/ns/today-entertainment/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100526010221/http://today.msnbc.msn.com/id/37302907/ns/today-entertainment/|url-status=dead|archive-date=May 26, 2010|title='Shrek Forever After' roars to top of box office|publisher=MSNBC|date=May 23, 2010|accessdate=May 23, 2010}}</ref> A sequel, ''[[Kung Fu Panda 2]]'', was released on May 26, 2011, along with a television series ''[[Kung Fu Panda: Legends of Awesomeness]]'' premiering on [[Nickelodeon]] later that same year as a part of [[Kung Fu Panda (franchise)|a franchise]]. A second sequel, ''[[Kung Fu Panda 3]]'',was released on January 29, 2016.\n\n== Plot ==\n<!-- Per WP:FILMPLOT, the plot summary should be around 400-700 words. Thank you. -->\nIn the Valley of Peace, a land in ancient China inhabited by anthropomorphic animals, Po Ping the [[giant panda]] is a [[Chinese martial arts|kung fu]] fanatic who idolizes the Furious Five \u2013 Tigress, Monkey, Crane, Viper, and Mantis \u2013 a quintet of awesome kung fu masters trained by Master Shifu, the [[red panda]]. However, Po is unable to pursue his dream of learning kung fu as he helps his adoptive father, Mr. Ping the goose, in his [[noodle]] restaurant.\n\nGrand Master Oogway, an old [[Gal\u00e1pagos tortoise]], Shifu's mentor and friend, has a vision that Shifu's former student and adoptive son, the evil [[snow leopard]], Tai Lung, will escape from prison and return to the valley to exact his revenge for being denied the [[Chinese dragon|Dragon]] Scroll, which is said to hold the secret to boundless power. Panicked, Shifu sends his messenger, Zeng the goose, with a request for the prison to tighten its security. He then holds a tournament for the Furious Five so that Oogway can identify the Dragon Warrior, the one kung fu master worthy of receiving the Dragon Scroll. Po arrives too late to enter the arena; desperate to see the Dragon Warrior, Po straps himself to a set of fireworks and launches himself into the middle of the arena in front of Oogway as he points towards the Dragon Warrior. To the astonishment of everyone present, Oogway proclaims Po as the chosen warrior.\n\nUnwilling to accept Oogway's decision, and believing it to be an accident, Shifu tries to dispose of Po with a harsh training regime. The Furious Five berate Po as an enthusiast with no potential in martial arts. Po considers resigning, but after receiving encouragement from Oogway, he endures his training and gradually befriends the Five with his durability, resilience, culinary skill, and good humor. One night when Po talks about Shifu's treatment toward him, Tigress tells the story of how Shifu raised Tai Lung since finding him as a cub and trained him in kung-fu. After Tai Lung was denied the Dragon Scroll he went on a rampage across the valley and tried to take the scroll by force, with Shifu unable to fight his adoptive son. Though Oogway was able to stop him, Tai Lung's betrayal caused Shifu to become cold and distant.\n\nMeanwhile, Tai Lung escapes from prison, ironically picking his locks with Zeng's fallen feather. Shifu horrifyingly learns of Tai Lung's escape from Zeng and informs Oogway, who extracts a promise from Shifu to believe in Po, and then [[Ascension (mystical)|passes on to the heavens]] in a stream of peach blossoms. Still unable to grasp the basics of kung fu, Po despairingly admits that he has no chance of defeating Tai Lung. Overhearing this, the Five leave to stop Tai Lung themselves. However, Shifu discovers that Po is capable of impressive physical feats when motivated by food. Using food as [[positive reinforcement]], Shifu successfully trains Po by incorporating these feats into an innovative kung fu style.\n\nMeanwhile, the Five battle with Tai Lung, but are defeated by his nerve attacks. He spares Crane to transport the rest of the Five, still paralyzed from his nerve strikes, back to Shifu as a warning. After reviving them, Shifu decides that Po is ready to receive the Dragon Scroll, but the scroll reveals nothing but a blank, reflective surface. Believing the scroll to be useless, Shifu orders Po and the Five to evacuate the valley while he faces Tai Lung. A distraught Po finds Mr. Ping. In an attempt to console his son, Mr. Ping reveals that the secret ingredient to his famous \"special secret ingredient noodle soup\" is \"nothing\", explaining that things are special when believed to be. Po realizes that this is the message of the Dragon Scroll and goes back to confront Tai Lung.\n \t\nPo arrives to find Shifu badly injured and defeated. He then becomes a formidable challenge for Tai Lung, frustrating him with confusing fighting techniques on top of his excessive body fat that renders him with an incredible ability to absorb damage and immunity to Tai Lung's nerve strikes. Tai Lung momentarily beats Po and retrieves the scroll, but he is unable to understand it and continues attacking Po. Eventually, Po defeats Tai Lung in combat by using the mysterious Wuxi Finger Hold to vanquish him.{{efn|In ''[[Kung Fu Panda 3]]'', it is revealed that using the Wuxi Finger Hold transports the opponent to the Spirit Realm.}} Po is praised by the Valley of Peace and earns the respect of the Furious Five, who fully acknowledge him as a true kung fu master, while Shifu finally attains peace.\n\n==Cast==\n{{see|List of Kung Fu Panda characters}}\n[[File:Kung Fu Panda The Five.jpg|upright=1.36|thumb|right|From left to right: Viper, Monkey, Mantis (on Monkey's head), Shifu, Tigress, and Crane. The Furious Five are homages to the actual [[Snake Kung Fu|Snake]], [[Monkey Kung Fu|Monkey]], [[Northern Praying Mantis|Praying Mantis]], [[Hung Ga|Tiger]], and [[Fujian White Crane|Crane]] styles of [[Chinese martial arts]].<ref>{{cite web |accessdate=September 1, 2008 |url=http://www.kungfupanda.com |title=''Kung Fu Panda''-production-five fighting warriors |publisher=DreamWorks}}</ref>]]\n* [[Jack Black]] as [[Po (Kung Fu Panda)|Po]], an energetic yet accident-prone [[giant panda]] and die-hard [[kung fu]] fan.\n* [[Dustin Hoffman]] as Master Shifu, an elderly and stern [[red panda]] and kung fu master to the Furious Five and Po.\n* The Furious Five:\n** [[Angelina Jolie]] as Master Tigress, a ruthless and ill-tempered [[South China tiger]] and leader of the Furious Five.\n** [[Seth Rogen]] as Master Mantis, a dry-humored [[Chinese mantis]].\n** [[Lucy Liu]] as Master Viper, a sweet and good-natured [[trimeresurus gramineus|green tree viper]].\n** [[David Cross]] as Master Crane, a pragmatic and sarcastic [[red-crowned crane]].\n** [[Jackie Chan]] as Master Monkey, an easygoing [[golden snub-nosed monkey]].\n* [[Ian McShane]] as Tai Lung, an arrogant and aggressive [[snow leopard]] who was formerly Shifu's adoptive son and student.\n* [[James Hong]] as Mr. Ping, Po's adoptive father, a happy-go-lucky [[Chinese goose]] who runs a noodle restaurant.\n* [[Randall Duk Kim]] as Grand Master Oogway, an ancient [[Gal\u00e1pagos tortoise]] and Shifu's mentor. \n* [[Dan Fogler]] as Zeng, a timid Chinese goose and Shifu's messenger.\n* [[Michael Clarke Duncan]] as Commander Vachir, a [[hubris]]tic and boastful [[Javan rhinoceros]] who is the warden of Chorh-Gom Prison, where Tai Lung is imprisoned.\n* [[Robert Clotworthy]] [[Steve Bulen]] and [[Mitch Carter]] as Anvil Of Heavens\n\n==Production==\n{{quote box|width=40%|quote= ... we love martial arts movies. I wasn't interested in making fun of them, because I really think martial arts movies can be great films, they can be as good as any genre movie when they're done properly ...\n\nLet's try to make it a real martial arts movie albeit one with a comic character and let's take our action seriously. Let's not give anything up to the big summer movies. Let's really make sure that our kung fu is as cool as any kung fu ever done, so that we can take our place in that canon and make sure it's a beautiful movie, because great martial arts movies are really beautiful-looking movies and then let's see if we can imbue it with real heart and emotion.|source= \u2014co-director [[John Stevenson (director)|John Stevenson]] on the comedic approach to the martial arts film.<ref name=\"John CS\">{{cite web|url=https://www.comingsoon.net/news/movienews.php?id=45494 |title=EXCL: ''Kung Fu Panda'' Co-Director John Stevenson |first=Edward |last=Douglas |work=ComingSoon.net |date=June 2, 2008 |accessdate=June 5, 2008}}</ref>}}\n\nPublicized work on the film began in October 2004.<ref>{{cite news|last=Aggerholm |first=Barbara |accessdate=September 16, 2017 |date=October 5, 2004 |work=[[Waterloo Region Record|Kitchener Record]] |url=http://www.tjgalda.com/About/Appearances_files/record_shark_some_bite.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080609204156/http://www.tjgalda.com/About/Appearances_files/record_shark_some_bite.html|archivedate=June 9, 2008|title=Giving a shark some bite; Local animator swims with the big boys}}</ref> In September 2005, [[DreamWorks Animation]] announced the film alongside [[Jack Black]], who was selected to be the main voice star.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.empireonline.com/News/story.asp?nid=17136 |title=Dreamworks Animation Plans Kung Fu Panda |magazine=[[Empire (magazine)|Empire]] |date=September 21, 2005 |accessdate=June 5, 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2005, DreamWorks Animation announced that [[Dustin Hoffman]], [[Jackie Chan]], [[Lucy Liu]] and [[Ian McShane]] would join Jack Black in the cast.<ref>{{cite news|publisher=UPI Entertainment News |date=November 9, 2005 |url=http://movies.about.com/od/moviesinproduction/a/kungfu110905.htm |title=DreamWorks Announces the Cast of ''Kung Fu Panda'' |accessdate=September 1, 2008}}</ref> This is also the second DreamWorks Animation film in which Black and [[Angelina Jolie]] have co-starred together, the first being 2004's ''[[Shark Tale]]''.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bowles|first1=Scott|title=Jolie, Black perfect for 'Kung Fu Panda 2'|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/movies/news/2011-05-06-kungfupanda06_cv_N.htm|accessdate=December 31, 2014|work=USA Today|date=May 6, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe idea for the film was conceived by Michael Lachance, a DreamWorks Animation executive.<ref>{{cite news|title=Imagi Announces Strategic Alliance for Gatchaman and Astro Boy Toy Development|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/press-release/2007-08-07/imagi-announces-strategic-alliance-for-gatchaman-and-astro-boy-toy-development|accessdate=March 22, 2012|newspaper=Anime News Network|date=August 7, 2007}}</ref> Initially, the idea was to make it a [[parody|spoof]], but co-director [[John Stevenson (director)|John Stevenson]] was not particularly keen on it and instead chose the direction of a character-based [[wuxia]] comedy.<ref name=\"John CS\"/>\n\nReportedly inspired by [[Stephen Chow]]'s 2004 [[martial arts film|martial arts]] action comedy film, ''[[Kung Fu Hustle]],''<ref>{{cite news|last=Gaul |first=Lou |date=November 4, 2005 |work=[[Bucks County, Pennsylvania#Industry and commerce|Bucks County Courier Times]] |url=https://news.google.com/archivesearch?q=%22Kung+Fu+Panda.%22+The+computer-animated+picture+was+reportedly+inspired+by+Stephen+Chow%27s+action+comedy%2C+%22Kung+Fu+Hustle.%22&btnG=Search+Archives&ned=us&ie=UTF-8 |title=1104 Film Clips |accessdate=September 1, 2008}}</ref> the co-directors wanted to make sure the film also had an authentic Chinese and kung fu feel to it. Production designer Raymond Zibach and art director Tang Heng spent years researching [[Chinese painting]], sculpture, architecture and kung fu films to help create the look of the film.<ref name=\"dailynews\">{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/movies/2008/06/01/2008-06-01_kung_fu_panda_gets_cuddly.html |title=''Kung Fu Panda'' gets cuddly |work=Daily News |location=New York |date=May 31, 2008 |accessdate=June 5, 2008}}</ref> Zibach said some of the biggest influences for him are the more artful martial arts films such as ''[[Hero (2002 film)|Hero]]'', ''[[House of Flying Daggers]]'' and ''[[Crouching Tiger, Hidden Dragon]]''.<ref name=\"dailynews\"/> Stevenson's aim for the film, which took four years to make, was to make \"the best looking film DreamWorks has ever made\".\n\n{{quote box|width=40%|quote= We've had some productions that were stressful, but this one ran very smoothly and DreamWorks is {{bracket|''sic''}} this production as a template on how they would like future productions to run. We lucked out, and there really was a sense of harmony on the animation. Even the production people. We all seemed like we were on the same page, believing in the film. That doesn't happen very often. I tell animators, you will be working on dumpers for most of your career, but every once in a while you get a gem. Kung Fu Panda was a gem.|source= \u2014Dan Wagner, Head of Character Animation.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://features.cgsociety.org/story_custom.php?story_id=4549&page=2 |title=''Kung Fu Panda'' - One For Life |first=Renne |last=Dunlop |work=CG Studios |accessdate=August 29, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080830074837/http://features.cgsociety.org/story_custom.php?story_id=4549&page=2 |archive-date=August 30, 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref>}}\n\nThe hand-drawn animation sequence at the beginning of the film was made to resemble Chinese [[Shadow play|shadow puppetry]].<ref name=\"twincities\">{{cite news|url=http://www.twincities.com/movies/ci_9488296?nclick_check=1 |title=''Kung Fu Panda'' is fresh, surprising and beautiful |first=Chris |last=Hewitt |work=TwinCities.com |date=June 6, 2008 |accessdate=June 7, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080609195347/http://www.twincities.com/movies/ci_9488296?nclick_check=1 |archivedate=June 9, 2008 }}</ref> The opening, which was directed by [[Jennifer Yuh Nelson]] and produced by [[James Baxter (animator)|James Baxter]], was praised by ''[[The New York Times]]'' reviewer [[Manohla Dargis]] as \"striking\" and \"visually different from most mainstream American animations\".<ref name=\"nyt\">{{cite news|url=https://movies.nytimes.com/2008/06/06/movies/06pand.html |title=Fuzzy Outsider, Kicking His Way Toward His Dream |first=Manohla |last=Dargis |work=The New York Times |date=June 6, 2008 |accessdate=June 10, 2008}}</ref>\n\nOther reviewers have compared the opening to the evocative style of [[Genndy Tartakovsky|Genndy Tartakovsky's]] [[Cartoon Network]] series ''[[Samurai Jack]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kungfucinema.com/?p=2198 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120629195720/http://www.kungfucinema.com/?p=2198 |url-status=dead |archive-date=June 29, 2012 |title=Kung Fu Cinemapoo ''Kung Fu Panda'' review |work=Kung Fu Cinema |accessdate=September 1, 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.timeout.com/film/newyork/reviews/85508/kung-fu-panda.html |title=Timeout ''Kung Fu Panda'' review |first=Stephen |last=Garrett |work=[[Time Out (company)|Time Out]] |accessdate=September 1, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080816161710/http://www.timeout.com/film/newyork/reviews/85508/kung-fu-panda.html |archivedate=August 16, 2008  }}</ref> The rest of the film is modern computer animation, which uses bright, offbeat colors to evoke the natural landscape of China.<ref name=\"twincities\"/> The end credit sequence also features hand-drawn characters and still paintings in the background.<ref name=\"twincities\"/>\n\nThe computer animation used throughout the film was more complex than anything DreamWorks had done before. When the head of production handed the script to VFX Supervisor Markus Manninen, she reportedly laughed and wished him \"good luck\". \"When we started talking,\" said Manninen, \"the movie was still a high concept. But for everyone that looked at it, it screamed complexity. We launched off saying, how can you make this movie tangible? How can you find smart ways to bring this world to life in a way that makes it a great movie and not feel like the complexity becomes the driver of the story, but the story and the emotion being the driver?\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://features.cgsociety.org/story_custom.php?story_id=4549 |title='Kung Fu Panda' |first=Renne |last=Dunlop |work=CG Studios |accessdate=August 29, 2008}}</ref> In preparation, the animators took a six-hour kung fu class.<ref name=\"Roberts1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.moviesonline.ca/movienews_14790.html |title=Jack Black Interview, Kung Fu Panda |accessdate=December 22, 2008 |last=Roberts |first=Sheila |work=MoviesOnline}}</ref>\n\nProducer Melissa Cobb said that originally Po was \"more of a jerk,\" but that the character changed after they heard Jack Black.<ref name=\"Roberts1\"/> According to Black, he mostly worked \"in isolation\", although he and Dustin Hoffman did spend a day together, which Cobb said helped with the scene where their characters face off.<ref name=\"Roberts1\"/> Lucy Liu said that the film \"was quite different because it was such a long process.\"<ref name=\"Roberts2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.moviesonline.ca/movienews_14789.html |title=Lucy Liu Interview, Kung Fu Panda |accessdate=December 22, 2008 |last=Roberts |first=Sheila |work=MoviesOnline}}</ref> Liu said that when she was presented with the project they already had artwork of her character as well as a \"short computerized video version of what she would look like when she moved.\"<ref name=\"Roberts2\"/>\n\n==Release==\nThe film held its worldwide premiere at the [[2008 Cannes Film Festival|61st Cannes Film Festival]] on May 15, 2008,<ref>{{cite news|title=DreamWorks Animation's 'Kung Fu Panda' Kicks Off Cannes Film Festival 2008|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2008/05/14/idUS240913+14-May-2008+PRN20080514|accessdate=March 28, 2012|agency=Reuters|date=May 14, 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120725172925/http://www.reuters.com/article/2008/05/14/idUS240913+14-May-2008+PRN20080514|archivedate=July 25, 2012}}</ref> where it received massive and sustained applause at the end of the film's screening.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/entertainmentNews/idUSN1631324020080516 |title=''Kung Fu Panda'' a martial arts masterpiece |agency=[[Reuters]] |date=May 16, 2008 |accessdate=June 1, 2008}}</ref> ''Kung Fu Panda'' later had national premieres in IMAX 3-D the US on June 1, 2008 at AMC & Regal Entertainment Group in [[Hollywood]], [[Los Angeles]], [[California]],<ref>{{cite news|last=Giardina|first=Carolyn|title=Helmers talk 'Kung Fu Panda'|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/helmers-talk-kung-fu-panda-112905|accessdate=March 27, 2012|newspaper=The Hollywood Reporter|date=June 1, 2008}}</ref> and on June 26, 2008 at [[Leicester Square]] in [[London]], for the UK.<ref>{{cite news|accessdate=September 10, 2008 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/newsbeat/hi/entertainment/newsid_7477000/7477138.stm |title=Kung Fu Panda London premiere |work=BBC |date=June 27, 2008}}</ref>\n\n===Home media===\n''Kung Fu Panda'' was released on [[DVD]] and [[Blu-ray Disc|Blu-ray]] on November 9, 2008,<ref name=CNWDVDBluray>{{cite press release|author1=DreamWorks Animation SKG|title=Pandamonium Breaks Loose on Sunday, November 9th When the Year's Biggest Comedy Debuts on DVD and Blu-ray Along With DreamWorks Animation's World Premiere of Po's All-New Adventure|url=http://www.newswire.ca/news-releases/pandamonium-breaks-loose-on-sunday-november-9th-when-the-years-biggest-comedy-debuts-on-dvd-and-blu-ray-along-with-dreamworks-animations-world-premiere-of-pos-all-new-adventure-536615491.html|publisher=CNW|accessdate=August 21, 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160821091249/http://www.newswire.ca/news-releases/pandamonium-breaks-loose-on-sunday-november-9th-when-the-years-biggest-comedy-debuts-on-dvd-and-blu-ray-along-with-dreamworks-animations-world-premiere-of-pos-all-new-adventure-536615491.html|archivedate=August 21, 2016|date=September 15, 2008|url-status=live}}</ref> and on 3D Blu-ray on December 6, 2011 as a Best Buy exclusive.<ref>{{cite news|title='Kung Fu Panda - 3D' and 'Kung Fu Panda 2 - 3D' Blu-ray 3D Best Buy Exclusives|url=http://bluray.highdefdigest.com/news/show/DreamWorks/Disc_Announcements/Kung_Fu_Panda_-_3D_and_Kung_Fu_Panda_2_-_3D_Blu-ray_3D_Best_Buy_Exclusives/8240|accessdate=March 27, 2012|newspaper=High-Def Digest|date=December 6, 2011}}</ref> The DVD double pack release of ''Kung Fu Panda'' also includes a short animated film ''[[Secrets of the Furious Five]]''.<ref name=CNWDVDBluray /> With 7,486,642 DVD units sold in 2008, ''Kung Fu Panda'' was the fourth highest-selling film and the first highest-selling animated film of 2008, right before ''[[WALL-E]]'', which sold 7,413,548 units.<ref>{{cite web|title=Top-Selling DVDs of 2008|url=https://www.the-numbers.com/dvd/charts/annual/2008.php|publisher=The Numbers|accessdate=March 27, 2012}}</ref> As of February 2010, 17.4 million home entertainment units were sold worldwide.<ref>https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/dreamworks-animation-reports-fourth-quarter-and-full-year-2009-financial-results-85085287.html</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Critical response===\n[[Rotten Tomatoes]] reported that 87% of 183 critics gave the film a positive review, with an average rating of 7.2/10. The website's critical consensus reads, \"''Kung Fu Panda'' has a familiar message, but the pleasing mix of humor, swift martial arts action, and colorful animation makes for winning summer entertainment.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/kung_fu_panda/ |title=Kung Fu Panda (2008) |accessdate=June 5, 2008 |publisher=[[Fandango Media]]|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]}}</ref> [[Metacritic]] reported the film had an average score of 73 out of 100, based on 33 reviews.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/kung-fu-panda |title=Kung Fu Panda Reviews |accessdate=June 5, 2008 |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|work=[[Metacritic]]}}</ref> Audience gave the film an average A- grade on CinemaScore.\n\n[[Richard Corliss]] of ''Time Magazine'' gave ''Kung Fu Panda'' a positive review, stating the picture \"provides a master course in cunning visual art and ultra-satisfying entertainment\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.time.com/time/arts/article/0,8599,1812145,00.html |title=''Kung Fu Panda'': Wise Heart, Sweet Art |work=Time |authorlink=Richard Corliss |first=Richard |last=Corliss |date=June 5, 2008 |accessdate=July 28, 2008}}</ref> ''The New York Times'' said, \"At once fuzzy-wuzzy and industrial strength, the tacky-sounding ''Kung Fu Panda'' is high concept with a heart,\" and the review called the film \"consistently diverting\" and \"visually arresting\".<ref name=\"nyt\"/> Chris Barsanti of ''[[Filmcritic.com]]'' commented, \"Blazing across the screen with eye-popping, sublime artwork, ''Kung Fu Panda'' sets itself apart from the modern domestic animation trend with its sheer beauty ... the film enters instant classic status as some of the most gorgeous animation Hollywood has produced since the golden age of Disney.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.filmcritic.com/misc/emporium.nsf/reviews/Kung-Fu-Panda |title='Kung Fu Panda' |first=Chris |last=Barsanti |work=Film Critic |accessdate=July 28, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080728045057/http://www.filmcritic.com/misc/emporium.nsf/reviews/Kung-Fu-Panda |archivedate=July 28, 2008  }}</ref> Michael Phillips of the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' called the film \"one of the few comedies of 2008 in any style or genre that knows what it's doing\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://chicago.metromix.com/movies/movie_review/movie-review-kung-fu/444443/content|title=Movie review: 'Kung Fu Panda'|last=Phillips|first=Michael|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|date=June 8, 2008|accessdate=May 30, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110430152733/http://chicago.metromix.com/movies/movie_review/movie-review-kung-fu/444443/content|archivedate=April 30, 2011}}</ref> However, Tom Charity of [[CNN]] criticized the action for tending \"to blur into a whirlwind of slapstick chaos\" and considered the character of Po too similar to others played by Black.<ref>{{cite web|first=Tom|last=Charity|url=http://www.cnn.com/2008/SHOWBIZ/Movies/06/06/review.panda/index.html|title=Review: 'Panda' is bear-ly good|publisher=[[CNN]]|date=June 6, 2008|accessdate=June 2, 2011}}</ref> Peter Howell of ''[[The Toronto Star]]'' awarded the film two and a half stars, considering it to have a \"lack of story\" that \"frequently manages to amuse, if not entirely to delight\".<ref>{{cite web|first=Peter|last=Howell|url=https://www.thestar.com/ParentCentral/Activities/article/438269|title=Kung Fu Panda: Panders to the predictable|work=[[The Toronto Star]]|date=June 6, 2008|accessdate=June 2, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Box office===\nThe film topped the box office in its opening weekend, grossing $60.2 million for a $14,642 average from 4,114 theaters<ref>{{cite web|url=https://boxofficemojo.com/weekend/chart/?yr=2008&wknd=23&p=.htm|title=Weekend Box Office Results for June 6\u20138, 2008|work=[[Box Office Mojo]]|date=June 8, 2008|accessdate=May 30, 2011}}</ref> and performing much better than analysts had been expecting.<ref name=\"DeadlineJun062008\">{{cite news|url=https://www.deadline.com/2008/06/kung-fu-panda-kicks-off-weekend-solid-1-adam-zandlers-zohan-close-2/|title=COMEDIES KICK BUTT! 'Kung Fu Panda' $60M Wkd; Adam Sandler's 'Zohan' $40M; #4 'Sex And The City' Nears $100M Cume|last=Finke|first=Nikki|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Mail.com Media]]|date=June 6, 2008|accessdate=May 30, 2011}}</ref> It also was the highest-grossing opening for a non-sequel DreamWorks Animation film at the time.<ref name=\"DeadlineJun062008\"/> In its second weekend, the film retreated 44% to second place behind ''[[The Incredible Hulk (film)|The Incredible Hulk]]'' grossing $33.6 million for a $8,127 average from expanding to 4,136 theaters.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://boxofficemojo.com/weekend/chart/?yr=2008&wknd=24&p=.htm|title=Weekend Box Office Results for June 13\u201315, 2008|work=[[Box Office Mojo]]|date=June 15, 2008|accessdate=May 30, 2011}}</ref> It closed on October 9, 2008 after 125 days of release, grossing $215.4 million in the United States and Canada and $416.3 million overseas for a worldwide total of $631.7 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=kungfupanda.htm|title=Kung Fu Panda (2008)|work=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=May 30, 2011}}</ref> ''Kung Fu Panda'' was the highest-grossing non-''Shrek'' film from DreamWorks Animation in the United States and Canada before it was surpassed by ''[[How to Train Your Dragon (film)|How to Train Your Dragon]]'' in 2010.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.slashfilm.com/how-to-train-you-dragon-has-become-dreamwork-animations-highest-grossing-non-shrek-movie/|title=How To Train Your Dragon Has Become Dreamwork Animation's Highest Grossing Non-Shrek Movie|last=Sciretta|first=Peter|publisher=[[/Film]]|date=June 30, 2010|accessdate=May 30, 2011}}</ref>\n\n''Kung Fu Panda'' was also well received in China.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.toonzone.net/article.php?ID=24549 |title=''Kung Fu Panda'' Received with Enthusiasm in Asia |work=Toonzone |accessdate=June 24, 2008}}</ref> It made nearly 110&nbsp;million [[Yuan (currency)|Yuan]] by July 2, 2008, becoming the first animated film to earn more than 100&nbsp;million Yuan in China.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/china/2268139/Kung-Fu-Panda-breaks-Chinese-box-office-records.html |title=Kung Fu Panda breaks Chinese box-office records |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=July 8, 2008 |accessdate=August 27, 2008 | location=London}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.cri.cn/3086/2008/07/08/1821s378282.htm |title=\"Kung Fu Panda\" Breaks Box Office Record of Animation |work=CriEnglish |date=July 8, 2008 |accessdate=August 27, 2008}}</ref> The Chinese director Lu Chuan commented, \"From a production standpoint, the movie is nearly perfect. Its American creators showed a very sincere attitude about Chinese culture.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2008/07/03/arts/AS-MOV-China-Kung-Fu-Panda.php |title=''Kung Fu Panda'' reaches Chinese box office milestone |work=International Herald Tribune  |accessdate=July 28, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/movies/news/2008-07-03-kungfupanda_N.htm |title=''Kung Fu Panda'' reaches Chinese box office milestone |work=USA Today  |accessdate=July 28, 2008 | date=July 3, 2008 | first=Min | last=Lee}}</ref> The film's critical and commercial success in China led to some local introspection about why no film like ''Kung Fu Panda'' had been produced in China, with commentators attributing the problem variously to lower film budgets in China, too much government oversight, a dearth of national imagination, and an overly reverent attitude to China's history and cultural icons.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/07/20/weekinreview/20bernstein.html |title=The Panda That Roared |last=Bernstein |first=Richard |date=July 20, 2008 |work=The New York Times  |accessdate=July 23, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/07/11/AR2008071103281.html |title=''Kung Fu Panda'' Hits A Sore Spot in China |last=Fan |first=Maureen |date=July 12, 2008 |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=July 23, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/audio/2008/jul/08/kungfu.panda.film |title=Kung Fu Panda: \"The director has really got in touch with what China is today\" |last=Watts |first=Jonathan |date=July 8, 2008 |work=The Guardian |accessdate=August 30, 2008 | location=London}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n''Kung Fu Panda'' was nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Animated Feature]]<ref name=Reuters3OscarBerths>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2008/11/11/us-oscars-idUSTRE4AA0YC20081111 |title=14 cartoons seek 3 Oscar berths |date=November 11, 2008 |agency=Reuters |accessdate=November 16, 2008}}</ref> and the [[Golden Globe Award for Best Animated Feature Film]],<ref name=Deadline66Golden /> but both awards were won by [[Pixar]]'s ''[[WALL-E]]''. Jack Black joked about his film's underdog status at the [[81st Academy Awards]], saying \"Each year, I do one DreamWorks project, then I take all the money to the Oscars and bet it on Pixar.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,1975321,00.html|title=Dreaming Up How to Train Your Dragon|last=Corliss|first=Richard|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|date=April 5, 2010|accessdate=May 30, 2011}}</ref>\n\nBy contrast, ''Kung Fu Panda'' won 10 [[Annie Awards]] (including Best Picture) out of 16 nominations, although this [[Annie Award#2009|created controversy]], with some accusing DreamWorks head [[Jeffrey Katzenberg]] of rigging the vote by buying [[ASIFA-Hollywood]] memberships (with voting power) for everyone at DreamWorks Animation.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://goldderby.latimes.com/awards_goldderby/2009/01/kung-fu-panda-d.html |title=''Kung Fu Panda'' dropkicks ''Wall-E'' at Annie Awards |work=Los Angeles Times |last=O'Neil |first=Tom |accessdate=July 12, 2009 | date=January 31, 2009}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Awards\n|-\n! Award\n! Category\n! Name\n! Outcome\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"|'''[[81st Academy Awards|Academy Awards]]'''<ref name=Reuters3OscarBerths />\n| [[Academy Award for Best Animated Feature]]\n| [[John Stevenson (director)|John Stevenson]]<br />[[Mark Osborne (filmmaker)|Mark Osborne]]\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n|style=\"border-top:10px black\" rowspan=16| '''[[36th Annie Awards|Annie Awards]]'''<ref>{{cite web|last1=Moody|first1=Annemarie|title=Oscar Nominations: Bolt, Kung Fu Panda and WALL-E Get Best Animated Feature Nods|url=http://www.awn.